% \begin{align}
\left(\trma - \trmb \right)\cdot \frac{dx}{dy} &= 1 \\ \implies \trma - \trmb &= \dydx \\ \text{or } \dydx + \underbrace{\trmb}_{P(x)} &= \trma \end{align} %text This looks like a \underline\text{first-order} linear differential equation with $P(x) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{x}}$ Hence $I = e^{\int P(x)\cdot dx} = e^{\int \frac{dx}{\sqrt{x}}} = e^{2\sqrt{x}}$%
